{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501197","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501197"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:25:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:25:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1731"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1731","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1731"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.11,0.04,0.71,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1731"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"5801"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1731","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1731"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1731"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"5801"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"325"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3193"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6903"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"5801","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/5801"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old man presents with a 24 hour history of pain in the right iliac fossa. He is on warfarin for atrial fibrillation and recently started a course of amoxicillin for a chest infection. On examination there is a tender mass in the right iliac fossa. The rest of the abdomen is soft. The mass is still palpable when the patient is asked to raise both his legs off the examination couch.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Appendix mass","Appendix abscess","Carcinoma of the caecum","Rectus sheath haematoma","Diverticular abscess"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Erectus sheath haematoma\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis in this case. The history of medicated atrial fibrillation makes a vascular cause for the patients\u0027 symptoms. Furthermore, the continued prominence of the mass when the patient raises his legs indicates it is likely to be present within the anterior abdominal wall. Whilst this is a superficial lesion, it is often difficult to work out on clinical grounds (particularly in the obese patient) if the lesion arises in the anterior abdominal wall or from within the peritoneal cavity. These haematomas are often of sudden onset and can cause the patient a great deal of pain, thus limiting the effectiveness of a sound clinical examination to delineate whether the lesion arises in, or deep to the anterior abdominal wall.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAppendix mass\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Eappendix abscess\u003C/strong\u003E are much less likely, as the patient presents with no history of fevers, or other constitutional symptoms. This also makes a diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Ediverticular abscess\u003C/strong\u003E less likely, particularly with no history of diverticular disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile the patient is within the most likely demographic for the development of \u003Cstrong\u003Ecarcinoma of the caecum\u003C/strong\u003E, the acute-onset of symptoms, with no associated constitutional symptoms (e.g. unintentional loss of weight, night sweats) makes this much less likely.  \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Rectus sheath haematomas must be considered in patients with sudden-onset abdominal pain with an associated localised mass"],"references":["Hatjipetrou A, Anyfantakis D, Kastanakis M. Rectus sheath hematoma: a review of the literature. International Journal of Surgery. 2015 Jan 1;13:267-71."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"5801"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1731"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"5801","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/5801"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2021-07-12T08:09:55+09:30","updatedAt":"2021-07-12T08:09:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1731"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"5801"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"crea